Data Structure and Algorithm 

SDLC (System Development Life Cycle) â Structure process in designing, developing and test the quality of software. (Step-by-step process of software development)
Phases of SDLC â Using the waterfall table and the realistic waterfall version
Problem, analysis and specification:
â¢	Small System (ComSci) â Easy, straight forward, minimal coding and self -contained
â¢	Large systems (Real world) â complex, tons of components, tons of coding, and at first, it is poorly defined.
-	Contract : purpose, precondition, postcondition.
-	Real world Contract: precision and to prove end product achieving the specification
Top down Design â table where looks like a tree diagram helps to break down task into smaller parts
Object Oriented Design:
 By identifying the following:
â¢	Problems specification and its objects and type.
â¢	Operation/task to manipulate the object
â¢	UML Class diagram 
Data type object 
â¢	Simple
â¢	Structure â Array, Structures and class objects 
Testing, Execution and debugging:
Validation â âAre we making the right product?â
o	Checking the documents, program modulesâ¦
o	Match the customer requirments
Verification â âAre we making the product rightâ
o	Check products if it is complete or correct
o	Have consistency
Different kinds of test required:
â¢	Unit test â Each component is tested individually
â¢	Integration test â testing components interface and information flow
â¢	System test â test the whole system 
Coding:
â¢	Language selection and encodes the design
Algorithm:
â¢	Pseudo code
â¢	Definite, easy to read, correct and efficient, and structured
â¢	You cannot separate algorithms to data structure
Types of error:
â¢	Syntax â error in grammar and language
â¢	Runtime â error program execution
â¢	Logic â messy algorithms design

Black box â Checks the correctness, Does not consider the structure of the and accepts input and output 
White box â Cares about what inside the structure of the code and individual program units are exercised.

Object Oriented Programming:
Procedural - action oriented that focuses verbs
â¢	Basic Task to do problems
â¢	Apply action to perform the task (subprograms)
â¢	Group subprograms (program/module/library)
â¢	Creating the system to solve the problem
Object-oriented â focus on nouns of the problem
â¢	What object needed to the problem
â¢	How do they work together to solve issues
â¢	Create classes (data members and function members)
â¢	Instances type called object (class)
Similarities of struct and classes:
â¢	Same syntax
â¢	Both Model objects and multiple attributes.
-	Data members/attributes
-	Fields
-	Instances and variable Attributes
â¢	Both Processes non-homogenous data sets.
Difference of struct and classes
	Class:
â¢	Private by default
â¢	Declared using class keyword
â¢	Used in abstraction and inheritance
Struct:
â¢	Public by default
â¢	Declared using struct key
â¢	Used in grouping of different data types
Types of data structure:
â¢	Simple data types (Int, double, floatâ¦)
â¢	Structured data types (ADT)
o	Array
o	Linked list
o	Stacks
o	Queue
o	Trees
o	Graphs
o	Hash tables


Array â contiguous, fixed, indexed, can accessed data anywhere, same data type
Data Structure â to organized data 
â¢	Data structures are Abstract data type (ADT)
Linked List â Fundamentals of data structure where you can use linked list in any type of data structure.
â¢	Dynamic, 
â¢	Head and tail
â¢	Linear data structure
â¢	Access data using pointers
â¢	Ease of insertion and deletion
Types of Linked List:
â¢	Singly Linked list 
â¢	Doubly linked list 
â¢	Circular linked list
Main Algorithms:
â¢	Insert at the end
â¢	Insert at the beginning 
â¢	Insert at the position
â¢	Delete at the end 
â¢	Delete at the beginning
â¢	Delete at the position

Stacks â FILO (First in Last Out) LIFO (Last in First Out) 
â¢	Can be limited (mostly limited)
Use of stacks:
â¢	Post-fix
â¢	In-fix
â¢	Post-fix to In-fix
â¢	You can also implement stacks in queue by using multiple stacks
â¢	Clipboard (Copy and paste)
â¢	Undo/Redo
â¢	Bracket matching
Main Algorithms
â¢	Pop (delete)
â¢	Push (Insert)
â¢	Top/Peek (Return the value at the Top of stacks)
â¢	Is Empty (to see if the stacks are empty)
Queue â FIFO (First in First Out) LILO (Last in Last Out) linear sequence data struct.
Types of Queues:
â¢	Linear Queue (Linked list)
â¢	Priority Queue
â¢	Circular Queue
Uses of stacks:
â¢	Task scheduling
â¢	Buffering
â¢	Customer services
â¢	Printer stooling
Main Algorithm:
â¢	Enqueue (Insert)
â¢	Dequeue (Delete)
â¢	Size (To view the size of the queue)
â¢	Peek ( View the first data in queue)

* Balance composition, symmetric

Some a mother letting her child sit on a lap, which usually happens in a Jeep
